THE presence of police officers on Zimbabwe’s roads has become a cause for concern for residents, business people and tourists who accuse the officers of corruption and extortion. This came out during a well-attended AMH Conversations discussion in Harare on Wednesday. <img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3096224743895331" src="https://www.newsday.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/IMG_9890.jpg" alt="IMG_9890" width="610" height="407" srcset="https://www.newsday.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/IMG_9890.jpg 610w, https://www.newsday.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/IMG_9890-300x200.jpg 300w, https://www.newsday.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/IMG_9890-100x67.jpg 100w, https://www.newsday.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/IMG_9890-200x133.jpg 200w, https://www.newsday.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/IMG_9890-185x124.jpg 185w" sizes="(max-width: 610px) 100vw, 610px" /> The conversation discussed the topic Impact of road blocks on civil liberties and productivity of our nation where ordinary citizens. The event was attended by civic activists, legal practitioners, business people and residents. Key speakers at the events included academic Ibbo Mandaza and Combined Harare Residents Association’s Mfundo Mlilo, Zimbabwe Council for Tourism president Francis Ngwenya, Florence Chagadama of Legal Resources Foundation and Kuda Hove. <img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3096224743895275" src="https://www.newsday.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/spot-fines-1.jpg" alt="spot fines 1" width="585" height="168" srcset="https://www.newsday.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/spot-fines-1.jpg 585w, https://www.newsday.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/spot-fines-1-300x86.jpg 300w, https://www.newsday.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/spot-fines-1-100x29.jpg 100w, https://www.newsday.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/spot-fines-1-200x57.jpg 200w" sizes="(max-width: 585px) 100vw, 585px" /> Curated tweets from people who were following and contributing to the conversation: <img clas